firm `\/publications\/` data integrity and publications JSON-LD.\n7. Add the three new reviews as drafts first.\n8. Resolve copyright\/version\/display rules.\n9. Publish new reviews one by one only after validation.\n10. Inventory and preserve legacy URLs.\n11. Prepare GitHub Pages deployment documentation\/workflow.\n12. Deploy live.\n13. Validate the live site and decide whether to remain on GitHub Pages or move\n    later to Netlify\/Cloudflare.\n```\n\nWhat I need to do now is add periodical, volume, and issue nodes to the JSON-LD, in all places where this would be desirable to have. What are the steps I need to take in order to implement this?\n\n> Below is a practical implementation sequence for adding `Periodical`,\n> `PublicationVolume`, and `PublicationIssue` nodes to the site’s JSON-LD without\n> disturbing the current Astro architecture.\n> \n> ## 1. Decide the target Schema.org pattern\n> \n> For journal-published articles\/reviews, use this nesting pattern:\n> \n> ```json\n> {\n>   \"@type\": [\"ScholarlyArticle\", \"Review\"],\n>   \"@id\": \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.xxxx\/example\",\n>   \"name\": \"Review of Example Book\",\n>   \"isPartOf\": {\n>     \"@type\": \"PublicationIssue\",\n>     \"@id\": \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/example\/#issue\",\n>     \"issueNumber\": \"2\",\n>     \"isPartOf\": {\n>       \"@type\": \"PublicationVolume\",\n>       \"@id\": \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/example\/#volume\",\n>       \"volumeNumber\": \"18\",\n>       \"isPartOf\": {\n>         \"@type\": \"Periodical\",\n>         \"@id\":\n> \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/example\/#periodical\",\n>         \"name\": \"Journal Name\",\n>         \"issn\": [\"1234-5678\", \"8765-4321\"]\n>       }\n>     }\n>   }\n> }\n> ```\n> \n> Use:\n> \n> ```text\n> Article\/Review\n>   isPartOf → PublicationIssue\n>     isPartOf → PublicationVolume\n>       isPartOf → Periodical\n> ```\n> \n> Do **not** attach journal\/volume\/issue metadata to the local manuscript node\n> unless the local node truly represents the published journal article. In the\n> current review model, this usually means:\n> \n> - local hosted review\/manuscript node: `#review`\n> - published DOI review node: DOI URL as `@id`\n> - periodical\/volume\/issue chain belongs primarily to the **published DOI review\n> node**\n> \n> For example:\n> \n> ```text\n> Local Review #review\n>   isBasedOn \/ citation → DOI Review\n> \n> DOI Review\n>   isPartOf → PublicationIssue → PublicationVolume → Periodical\n> ```\n> \n> That preserves the distinction between the hosted local page and the published\n> version.\n> \n> ---\n> \n> ## 2. Add journal\/periodical metadata to the content schema\n> \n> Open:\n> \n> ```text\n> src\/content.config.ts\n> ```\n> \n> Find the `reviews` collection schema. Add optional fields for the published\n> review’s journal metadata.\n> \n> A possible shape:\n> \n> ```ts\n> const periodicalSchema = z.object({\n>   name: z.string(),\n>   issn: z.array(z.string()).optional(),\n>   printIssn: z.string().optional(),\n>   electronicIssn: z.string().optional(),\n>   url: z.string().url().optional(),\n>   publisher: z.string().optional(),\n> }).optional();\n> \n> const publicationContainerSchema = z.object({\n>   periodical: periodicalSchema,\n>   volume: z.string().optional(),\n>   issue: z.string().optional(),\n>   articleId: z.string().optional(),\n>   pageStart: z.string().optional(),\n>   pageEnd: z.string().optional(),\n>   pagination: z.string().optional(),\n> }).optional();\n> ```\n> \n> Then include it wherever your review frontmatter currently stores\n> published-review metadata.\n> \n> For example, if your current schema has something like:\n> \n> ```ts\n> publishedReview: z.object({\n>   doi: z.string().optional(),\n>   url: z.string().url().optional(),\n>   datePublished: z.string().optional(),\n> }).optional(),\n> ```\n> \n> extend it:\n> \n> ```ts\n> publishedReview: z.object({\n>   doi: z.string().optional(),\n>   url: z.string().url().optional(),\n>   datePublished: z.string().optional(),\n> \n>   periodical: z.object({\n>     name: z.string(),\n>     issn: z.array(z.string()).optional(),\n>     printIssn: z.string().optional(),\n>     electronicIssn: z.string().optional(),\n>     url: z.string().url().optional(),\n>     publisher: z.string().optional(),\n>   }).optional(),\n> \n>   volume: z.string().optional(),\n>   issue: z.string().optional(),\n>   articleId: z.string().optional(),\n>   pageStart: z.string().optional(),\n>   pageEnd: z.string().optional(),\n>   pagination: z.string().optional(),\n> }).optional(),\n> ```\n> \n> If publication-list items have their own collection, also update:\n> \n> ```text\n> src\/content\/publication-items\/\n> ```\n> \n> and the corresponding schema in `src\/content.config.ts`.\n> \n> You want the same kind of optional journal metadata available to\n> bibliography-only items.\n> \n> ---\n> \n> ## 3. Add metadata to the review Markdown files\n> \n> For example, in:\n> \n> ```text\n> src\/content\/reviews\/christian-right-europe.md\n> ```\n> \n> add or extend the published-review metadata.\n> \n> A likely shape would be:\n> \n> ```yaml\n> publishedReview:\n>   doi: \"10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\"\n>   url: \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\"\n>   datePublished: \"2025-07-25\"\n>   periodical:\n>     name: \"Journal of Church and State\"\n>     issn:\n>       - \"0021-969X\"\n>       - \"2040-4867\"\n>     url: \"https:\/\/academic.oup.com\/jcs\"\n>     publisher: \"Oxford University Press\"\n>   volume: \"67\"\n>   issue: \"3\"\n>   articleId: \"csaf039\"\n> ```\n> \n> Use the exact values you have verified.\n> \n> If page range is available:\n> \n> ```yaml\n>   pageStart: \"123\"\n>   pageEnd: \"126\"\n>   pagination: \"123–126\"\n> ```\n> \n> If the publication uses only an article ID, do not invent pages.\n> \n> For `cosmic-connections.md`, only add periodical\/volume\/issue metadata if the\n> published DOI version has verified journal\/container details.\n> \n> ---\n> \n> ## 4. Create a helper for publication container nodes\n> \n> To avoid duplicating periodical\/volume\/issue logic in several schema files,\n> create a helper.\n> \n> For example:\n> \n> ```text\n> src\/data\/schema\/helpers\/createPublicationContainer.ts\n> ```\n> \n> Suggested helper:\n> \n> ```ts\n> import { nodeId } from \"..\/..\/site\";\n> \n> type PeriodicalData = {\n>   name: string;\n>   issn?: string[];\n>   printIssn?: string;\n>   electronicIssn?: string;\n>   url?: string;\n>   publisher?: string;\n> };\n> \n> type ContainerData = {\n>   periodical?: PeriodicalData;\n>   volume?: string;\n>   issue?: string;\n> };\n> \n> type ContainerOptions = {\n>   pagePath: string;\n> };\n> \n> export function createPublicationContainer(\n>   container: ContainerData | undefined,\n>   options: ContainerOptions\n> ) {\n>   if (!container?.periodical?.name) {\n>     return undefined;\n>   }\n> \n>   const periodical: Record<string, unknown> = {\n>     \"@type\": \"Periodical\",\n>     \"@id\": nodeId(options.pagePath, \"periodical\"),\n>     name: container.periodical.name,\n>   };\n> \n>   const issnValues = [\n>     ...(container.periodical.issn ?? []),\n>     container.periodical.printIssn,\n>     container.periodical.electronicIssn,\n>   ].filter(Boolean);\n> \n>   if (issnValues.length === 1) {\n>     periodical.issn = issnValues[0];\n>   } else if (issnValues.length > 1) {\n>     periodical.issn = issnValues;\n>   }\n> \n>   if (container.periodical.url) {\n>     periodical.url = container.periodical.url;\n>   }\n> \n>   if (container.periodical.publisher) {\n>     periodical.publisher = {\n>       \"@type\": \"Organization\",\n>       name: container.periodical.publisher,\n>     };\n>   }\n> \n>   if (container.volume) {\n>     const volume: Record<string, unknown> = {\n>       \"@type\": \"PublicationVolume\",\n>       \"@id\": nodeId(options.pagePath, \"volume\"),\n>       volumeNumber: container.volume,\n>       isPartOf: periodical,\n>     };\n> \n>     if (container.issue) {\n>       return {\n>         \"@type\": \"PublicationIssue\",\n>         \"@id\": nodeId(options.pagePath, \"issue\"),\n>         issueNumber: container.issue,\n>         isPartOf: volume,\n>       };\n>     }\n> \n>     return volume;\n>   }\n> \n>   if (container.issue) {\n>     return {\n>       \"@type\": \"PublicationIssue\",\n>       \"@id\": nodeId(options.pagePath, \"issue\"),\n>       issueNumber: container.issue,\n>       isPartOf: periodical,\n>     };\n>   }\n> \n>   return periodical;\n> }\n> ```\n> \n> This gives you a single reusable way to build:\n> \n> ```text\n> Periodical\n> PublicationVolume\n> PublicationIssue\n> ```\n> \n> and avoids accidental inconsistencies.\n> \n> ---\n> \n> ## 5. Add the container chain to `createReviewSchema.ts`\n> \n> Open:\n> \n> ```text\n> src\/data\/schema\/reviews\/createReviewSchema.ts\n> ```\n> \n> Import the helper:\n> \n> ```ts\n> import { createPublicationContainer } from\n> \"..\/helpers\/createPublicationContainer\";\n> ```\n> \n> Check the relative path from the actual file location; it may need to be:\n> \n> ```ts\n> import { createPublicationContainer } from\n> \"..\/..\/helpers\/createPublicationContainer\";\n> ```\n> \n> depending on where you place the helper.\n> \n> Inside `createReviewSchema(review)`, identify where the published DOI review\n> node is created.\n> \n> It probably has a shape similar to:\n> \n> ```ts\n> const publishedReview = {\n>   \"@type\": [\"ScholarlyArticle\", \"Review\"],\n>   \"@id\": publishedReviewId,\n>   name: publishedReviewName,\n>   headline: publishedReviewName,\n>   author: personRef,\n>   datePublished: review.publishedReview?.datePublished,\n>   itemReviewed: reviewedWorkRef,\n> };\n> ```\n> \n> Add:\n> \n> ```ts\n> const publicationContainer = createPublicationContainer(review.publishedReview,\n> {\n>   pagePath: `\/publications\/reviews\/${review.slug}\/`,\n> });\n> ```\n> \n> Then attach it to the published DOI review node:\n> \n> ```ts\n> if (publicationContainer) {\n>   publishedReview.isPartOf = publicationContainer;\n> }\n> ```\n> \n> Also add article\/page metadata where available:\n> \n> ```ts\n> if (review.publishedReview?.pagination) {\n>   publishedReview.pagination = review.publishedReview.pagination;\n> }\n> \n> if (review.publishedReview?.pageStart) {\n>   publishedReview.pageStart = review.publishedReview.pageStart;\n> }\n> \n> if (review.publishedReview?.pageEnd) {\n>   publishedReview.pageEnd = review.publishedReview.pageEnd;\n> }\n> \n> if (review.publishedReview?.articleId) {\n>   publishedReview.identifier = [\n>     ...(Array.isArray(publishedReview.identifier)\n>       ? publishedReview.identifier\n>       : publishedReview.identifier\n>         ? [publishedReview.identifier]\n>         : []),\n>     {\n>       \"@type\": \"PropertyValue\",\n>       propertyID: \"Article ID\",\n>       value: review.publishedReview.articleId,\n>     },\n>   ];\n> }\n> ```\n> \n> If DOI identifiers are already being added, preserve them. Do not let `@id`\n> become an array.\n> \n> A clean published review node may end up looking like:\n> \n> ```ts\n> const publishedReview: Record<string, unknown> = {\n>   \"@type\": [\"ScholarlyArticle\", \"Review\"],\n>   \"@id\": publishedReviewId,\n>   name: publishedReviewName,\n>   headline: publishedReviewName,\n>   author: personRef,\n>   datePublished: review.publishedReview?.datePublished,\n>   itemReviewed: reviewedWorkRef,\n> };\n> \n> const publicationContainer = createPublicationContainer(review.publishedReview,\n> {\n>   pagePath: `\/publications\/reviews\/${review.slug}\/`,\n> });\n> \n> if (publicationContainer) {\n>   publishedReview.isPartOf = publicationContainer;\n> }\n> \n> if (review.publishedReview?.articleId) {\n>   publishedReview.identifier = [\n>     {\n>       \"@type\": \"PropertyValue\",\n>       propertyID: \"Article ID\",\n>       value: review.publishedReview.articleId,\n>     },\n>   ];\n> }\n> \n> if (review.publishedReview?.pagination) {\n>   publishedReview.pagination = review.publishedReview.pagination;\n> }\n> \n> if (review.publishedReview?.pageStart) {\n>   publishedReview.pageStart = review.publishedReview.pageStart;\n> }\n> \n> if (review.publishedReview?.pageEnd) {\n>   publishedReview.pageEnd = review.publishedReview.pageEnd;\n> }\n> ```\n> \n> ---\n> \n> ## 6. Do not add the periodical chain to the local review node by default\n> \n> For the current model, avoid this:\n> \n> ```json\n> {\n>   \"@id\":\n> \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#review\n> \",\n>   \"isPartOf\": {\n>     \"@type\": \"Periodical\"\n>   }\n> }\n> ```\n> \n> unless the local node is explicitly the published Version of Record.\n> \n> Instead, keep the local node as:\n> \n> ```json\n> {\n>   \"@id\":\n> \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#review\n> \",\n>   \"@type\": [\"ScholarlyArticle\", \"Review\"],\n>   \"isBasedOn\": {\n>     \"@id\": \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\"\n>   },\n>   \"citation\": {\n>     \"@id\": \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\"\n>   }\n> }\n> ```\n> \n> and put journal metadata on:\n> \n> ```json\n> {\n>   \"@id\": \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\",\n>   \"@type\": [\"ScholarlyArticle\", \"Review\"],\n>   \"isPartOf\": {\n>     \"@type\": \"PublicationIssue\"\n>   }\n> }\n> ```\n> \n> ---\n> \n> ## 7. Add the same capability to publications-page JSON-LD\n> \n> Open:\n> \n> ```text\n> src\/data\/schema\/publications\/createPublicationsSchema.ts\n> ```\n> \n> This schema should model:\n> \n> ```text\n> CollectionPage\n>   mainEntity → ItemList\n>     itemListElement → ListItem[]\n> ```\n> \n> For each `ListItem.item`, if the item represents a journal article\/review with\n> verified metadata, add the same `isPartOf` chain.\n> \n> You have two options.\n> \n> ### Option A: use the same helper directly\n> \n> Where you build a publication item schema object, add:\n> \n> ```ts\n> const publicationContainer = createPublicationContainer(item, {\n>   pagePath: item.localPath ?? \"\/publications\/\",\n> });\n> \n> if (publicationContainer) {\n>   creativeWork.isPartOf = publicationContainer;\n> }\n> ```\n> \n> However, if multiple bibliography items are listed on `\/publications\/`, using:\n> \n> ```ts\n> nodeId(\"\/publications\/\", \"periodical\")\n> ```\n> \n> would create duplicate IDs. So for publication-list items, you need\n> item-specific fragments.\n> \n> For example:\n> \n> ```ts\n> pagePath: \"\/publications\/\",\n> fragmentPrefix: item.slug\n> ```\n> \n> You may want to adjust the helper to accept explicit fragment IDs.\n> \n> Better helper signature:\n> \n> ```ts\n> type ContainerOptions = {\n>   baseIdPath: string;\n>   idPrefix?: string;\n> };\n> ```\n> \n> Then IDs can become:\n> \n> ```text\n> https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/#christian-right-europe-periodical\n> https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/#christian-right-europe-volume\n> https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/#christian-right-europe-issue\n> ```\n> \n> For review pages, they can remain:\n> \n> ```text\n> https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#\n> periodical\n> https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#volume\n> https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#issue\n> ```\n> \n> ### Option B: only include rich container metadata on canonical item pages\n> \n> This is simpler and safer.\n> \n> On `\/publications\/`, you can keep the `ItemList` modest and only include:\n> \n> ```json\n> {\n>   \"@type\": \"ListItem\",\n>   \"position\": 1,\n>   \"item\": {\n>     \"@type\": \"ScholarlyArticle\",\n>     \"@id\": \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\",\n>     \"name\": \"Review of The Christian Right in Europe\"\n>   }\n> }\n> ```\n> \n> Then put full periodical\/volume\/issue metadata on the dedicated review page.\n> \n> This is probably the cleaner Stage 3 approach unless you specifically want\n> `\/publications\/` to carry fuller bibliography JSON-LD.\n> \n> ---\n> \n> ## 8. Update publication-item frontmatter where relevant\n> \n> For bibliography-only entries in:\n> \n> ```text\n> src\/content\/publication-items\/\n> ```\n> \n> add optional metadata only where verified.\n> \n> Example:\n> \n> ```yaml\n> type: \"ScholarlyArticle\"\n> title: \"Example Article Title\"\n> doi: \"10.xxxx\/example\"\n> datePublished: \"2023-06-01\"\n> periodical:\n>   name: \"Example Journal\"\n>   issn:\n>     - \"1234-5678\"\n> volume: \"12\"\n> issue: \"1\"\n> pageStart: \"45\"\n> pageEnd: \"67\"\n> pagination: \"45–67\"\n> ```\n> \n> Do not add journal metadata to books, chapters, thesis items, or local-only\n> manuscripts unless appropriate.\n> \n> ---\n> \n> ## 9. Use DOI URLs as IDs for published articles\n> \n> For published DOI review\/article nodes, keep this rule:\n> \n> ```text\n> DOI URL = @id\n> ```\n> \n> Example:\n> \n> ```json\n> \"@id\": \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\"\n> ```\n> \n> Do not use a local fragment ID for the published article if a DOI exists.\n> \n> Local fragment IDs are appropriate for site-specific supporting nodes such as:\n> \n> ```text\n> #webpage\n> #review\n> #periodical\n> #volume\n> #issue\n> ```\n> \n> But for the actual DOI article:\n> \n> ```text\n> https:\/\/doi.org\/...\n> ```\n> \n> is better.\n> \n> ---\n> \n> ## 10. Normalize DOI handling before using DOI IDs\n> \n> If not already done, add or harden a DOI helper.\n> \n> Possible file:\n> \n> ```text\n> src\/data\/schema\/helpers\/doi.ts\n> ```\n> \n> Example:\n> \n> ```ts\n> export function normalizeDoi(input?: string): string | undefined {\n>   if (!input) return undefined;\n> \n>   return input\n>     .trim()\n>     .replace(\/^https?:\\\/\\\/(dx\\.)?doi\\.org\\\/\/i, \"\")\n>     .replace(\/^doi:\\s*\/i, \"\");\n> }\n> \n> export function doiUrl(input?: string): string | undefined {\n>   const doi = normalizeDoi(input);\n>   return doi ? `https:\/\/doi.org\/${doi}` : undefined;\n> }\n> ```\n> \n> Use it in both:\n> \n> ```text\n> createReviewSchema.ts\n> createPublicationsSchema.ts\n> ```\n> \n> This prevents inconsistent IDs such as:\n> \n> ```text\n> https:\/\/dx.doi.org\/...\n> http:\/\/doi.org\/...\n> doi:10....\n> 10....\n> ```\n> \n> ---\n> \n> ## 11. Validate Christian Right first\n> \n> Use the Christian Right review as the first test case because it already has a\n> DOI and known journal-style metadata.\n> \n> Target structure:\n> \n> ```text\n> Published DOI Review:\n> https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\n> \n> isPartOf:\n>   PublicationIssue\n>     issueNumber: verified issue\n>     isPartOf:\n>       PublicationVolume\n>         volumeNumber: verified volume\n>         isPartOf:\n>           Periodical\n>             name: Journal of Church and State\n>             issn: verified ISSNs\n> ```\n> \n> Run:\n> \n> ```bash\n> npx astro sync\n> npx astro check\n> npm run build\n> npm run preview\n> ```\n> \n> Then inspect rendered JSON-LD at:\n> \n> ```text\n> http:\/\/localhost:4321\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/\n> ```\n> \n> Check that:\n> \n> - the DOI review node has `isPartOf`;\n> - the local `#review` node does not falsely claim to be part of the journal\n> unless intended;\n> - `@id` values are strings, not arrays;\n> - `Periodical`, `PublicationVolume`, and `PublicationIssue` are nested\n> correctly;\n> - no periodical metadata appears on unrelated pages.\n> \n> ---\n> \n> ## 12. Then add Cosmic Connections if appropriate\n> \n> For:\n> \n> ```text\n> src\/content\/reviews\/cosmic-connections.md\n> ```\n> \n> be especially careful because the local page is an unabridged Original\n> Submission \/ Author Manuscript and materially different from the published\n> version.\n> \n> The correct pattern remains:\n> \n> ```text\n> Local #review\n>   isBasedOn \/ citation → published DOI review\n> \n> Published DOI review\n>   isPartOf → PublicationIssue → PublicationVolume → Periodical\n> ```\n> \n> Do **not** use `sameAs`.\n> \n> ---\n> \n> ## 13. Check whether CV schema needs this data\n> \n> Open:\n> \n> ```text\n> src\/data\/schema\/cv.ts\n> ```\n> \n> If the CV schema merely describes the CV page, Person, and PDF, you probably do\n> **not** need periodical\/volume\/issue nodes there.\n> \n> Only add periodical\/volume\/issue metadata to CV JSON-LD if the CV schema\n> explicitly lists individual scholarly works as structured `ScholarlyArticle` or\n> `Review` nodes.\n> \n> In Stage 3, it is probably better to keep the CV schema modest and put rich\n> publication metadata on:\n> \n> ```text\n> \/publications\/\n> \/publications\/reviews\/<slug>\/\n> ```\n> \n> ---\n> \n> ## 14. Avoid adding this to homepage JSON-LD\n> \n> Do not add `Periodical`, `PublicationVolume`, or `PublicationIssue` nodes to:\n> \n> ```text\n> src\/data\/schema\/home.ts\n> ```\n> \n> The homepage graph should remain focused on:\n> \n> ```text\n> ImageObject\n> Person\n> WebSite\n> AboutPage\n> ```\n> \n> Publication-container metadata belongs on publication\/review pages, not the\n> homepage.\n> \n> ---\n> \n> ## 15. Recommended implementation order\n> \n> Do the work in this order:\n> \n> 1. Add optional periodical\/container fields to `src\/content.config.ts`.\n> 2. Add verified metadata to `christian-right-europe.md`.\n> 3. Create a helper such as:\n> \n>    ```text\n>    src\/data\/schema\/helpers\/createPublicationContainer.ts\n>    ```\n> \n> 4. Import the helper into:\n> \n>    ```text\n>    src\/data\/schema\/reviews\/createReviewSchema.ts\n>    ```\n> \n> 5. Attach the resulting `isPartOf` chain to the **published DOI review node**,\n> not the local review node.\n> 6. Run:\n> \n>    ```bash\n>    npx astro sync\n>    npx astro check\n>    npm run build\n>    ```\n> \n> 7. Inspect rendered JSON-LD in local preview.\n> 8. Validate with Schema Markup Validator.\n> 9. Repeat for `cosmic-connections.md` if verified container metadata is\n> available.\n> 10. Decide whether `\/publications\/` should include full container metadata or\n> only modest `ItemList` entries.\n> 11. If desired, add the same helper to `createPublicationsSchema.ts`.\n> 12. Rebuild and revalidate `\/publications\/`.\n> \n> ---\n> \n> ## 16. Minimal example of desired Christian Right output\n> \n> The rendered JSON-LD should contain something conceptually like this:\n> \n> ```json\n> {\n>   \"@type\": [\"ScholarlyArticle\", \"Review\"],\n>   \"@id\": \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\",\n>   \"name\": \"Review of The Christian Right in Europe\",\n>   \"headline\": \"Review of The Christian Right in Europe\",\n>   \"author\": {\n>     \"@id\": \"https:\/\/orcid.org\/0000-0002-2599-3227\"\n>   },\n>   \"datePublished\": \"2025-07-25\",\n>   \"itemReviewed\": {\n>     \"@id\": \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1515\/9783839460382\"\n>   },\n>   \"identifier\": [\n>     {\n>       \"@type\": \"PropertyValue\",\n>       \"propertyID\": \"Article ID\",\n>       \"value\": \"csaf039\"\n>     }\n>   ],\n>   \"isPartOf\": {\n>     \"@type\": \"PublicationIssue\",\n>     \"@id\":\n> \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#issue\"\n> ,\n>     \"issueNumber\": \"3\",\n>     \"isPartOf\": {\n>       \"@type\": \"PublicationVolume\",\n>       \"@id\":\n> \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#volume\n> \",\n>       \"volumeNumber\": \"67\",\n>       \"isPartOf\": {\n>         \"@type\": \"Periodical\",\n>         \"@id\":\n> \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#\n> periodical\",\n>         \"name\": \"Journal of Church and State\",\n>         \"issn\": [\"0021-969X\", \"2040-4867\"],\n>         \"publisher\": {\n>           \"@type\": \"Organization\",\n>           \"name\": \"Oxford University Press\"\n>         }\n>       }\n>     }\n>   }\n> }\n> ```\n> \n> Use exact verified `volume`, `issue`, ISSNs, and publisher values.\n> \n> ---\n> \n> The main principle: add periodical\/volume\/issue metadata to the **published\n> scholarly work nodes**, especially DOI-identified review\/article nodes, and\n> avoid implying that local author manuscripts or hosted pages are themselves\n> journal issues or journal publications unless that is explicitly true.\n\n26 May 2026 at 13:53:01 BST\n\n# JSON-LD check after implementation\n\nAfter implementing the above-described changes, the JSON-LD of christian-right-europe is currently this:\n\n```json\n{\n      \"@context\": \"https:\/\/schema.org\",\n      \"@graph\": [\n        {\n          \"@id\": \"https:\/\/orcid.org\/0000-0002-2599-3227\",\n          \"@type\": \"Person\",\n          \"name\": \"Stevan Veljkovic\",\n          \"url\": \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/\",\n          \"identifier\": {\n            \"@type\": \"PropertyValue\",\n            \"propertyID\": \"ORCID\",\n            \"value\": \"0000-0002-2599-3227\",\n            \"url\": \"https:\/\/orcid.org\/0000-0002-2599-3227\"\n          }\n        },\n        {\n          \"@id\": \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/#website\",\n          \"@type\": \"WebSite\",\n          \"url\": \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/\",\n          \"name\": \"Stevan Veljkovic\",\n          \"inLanguage\": \"en-GB\",\n          \"publisher\": {\n            \"@id\": \"https:\/\/orcid.org\/0000-0002-2599-3227\"\n          }\n        },\n        {\n          \"@id\": \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#webpage\",\n          \"@type\": \"WebPage\",\n          \"url\": \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/\",\n          \"name\": \"Review of The Christian Right in Europe\",\n          \"description\": \"This repository of rich and useful scholarship is bound together by a tendentious thesis, wr