039\",\n    \"url\": \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"@type\": \"PropertyValue\",\n    \"propertyID\": \"Article ID\",\n    \"value\": \"csaf039\"\n  }\n]\n```\n\nThat brings the review page into line with the `\/publications\/` page. I would now regard the **periodical \/ volume \/ issue JSON-LD task as complete**, with a few adjacent metadata\/date refinements consciously deferred to later tasks.\n\nBelow is a project-memory delta note you can retain for the worksheet closeout.\n\n---\n\n```md\n# Project-memory delta: periodical, volume, and issue JSON-LD implementation\n\nDate: 2026-05-26\n\n## Summary\n\nThe site’s publication\/review JSON-LD has been extended to include periodical,\nvolume, and issue nodes where appropriate.\n\nThe implemented pattern is:\n\n```text\nScholarlyArticle \/ Review\n  isPartOf → PublicationIssue\n    isPartOf → PublicationVolume\n      isPartOf → Periodical\n```\n\nThis is now present on:\n\n```text\n\/publications\/\n\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/\n```\n\nThe periodical\/volume\/issue task can be treated as materially complete.\n\n## Christian Right review page JSON-LD\n\nCurrent route:\n\n```text\n\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/\n```\n\nThe Christian Right review-page JSON-LD now includes:\n\n```text\nPerson:\nhttps:\/\/orcid.org\/0000-0002-2599-3227\n\nWebSite:\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/#website\n\nWebPage:\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#webpage\n\nReviewed Book:\nhttps:\/\/doi.org\/10.1515\/9783839460382\n\nPublished DOI Review:\nhttps:\/\/doi.org\/10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\n\nPeriodical:\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#periodical\n\nPublicationVolume:\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#volume\n\nPublicationIssue:\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#issue\n\nLocal Review:\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#review\n```\n\nThe DOI-identified published review node now points to the issue:\n\n```json\n\"isPartOf\": {\n  \"@id\": \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#issue\"\n}\n```\n\nThe issue points to the volume, and the volume points to the periodical.\n\nThe local hosted review node remains separate:\n\n```text\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#review\n```\n\nand continues to cite \/ be based on the DOI node:\n\n```json\n\"isBasedOn\": {\n  \"@id\": \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\"\n},\n\"citation\": {\n  \"@id\": \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\"\n}\n```\n\nThis preserves the distinction between:\n\n1. Stevan as `Person`;\n2. the reviewed book;\n3. the published DOI review;\n4. the local hosted review\/page representation;\n5. the journal issue\/volume\/periodical container.\n\n## Christian Right periodical metadata\n\nThe Christian Right periodical chain currently uses:\n\n```text\nPeriodical:\nJournal of Church and State\n\nPeriodical URL:\nhttps:\/\/academic.oup.com\/jcs\n\nISSNs:\n0021-969X\n2040-4867\n\nPublisher:\nOxford University Press\n\nVolume:\n67\n\nIssue:\n3\n\nIssue URL:\nhttps:\/\/academic.oup.com\/jcs\/issue\/67\/3\/\n\nIssue image:\nhttps:\/\/oup.silverchair-cdn.com\/oup\/backfile\/Content_public\/Journal\/jcs\/Issue\/67\/3\/15\/m_jcs_67_3cover.jpeg\n```\n\nCurrent issue-level date:\n\n```json\n\"datePublished\": \"2025-07-01\"\n```\n\nNote: this should remain only if the exact issue publication date has been\nverified. If it merely means “July 2025”, later date cleanup should reduce it to\n`2025-07` or omit it.\n\n## Christian Right DOI\/article identifiers\n\nA consistency issue was fixed.\n\nThe Christian Right DOI review node on the review page now matches the\n`\/publications\/` page by including both the DOI and article ID:\n\n```json\n\"identifier\": [\n  {\n    \"@type\": \"PropertyValue\",\n    \"propertyID\": \"DOI\",\n    \"value\": \"10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\",\n    \"url\": \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\"\n  },\n  {\n    \"@type\": \"PropertyValue\",\n    \"propertyID\": \"Article ID\",\n    \"value\": \"csaf039\"\n  }\n]\n```\n\nDecision: `csaf039` should be treated as an article identifier, not as\n`pagination`.\n\n## Publications page JSON-LD\n\nThe `\/publications\/` page now includes periodical\/volume\/issue nodes for entries\nwhere metadata has been supplied.\n\nCurrent route:\n\n```text\n\/publications\/\n```\n\nThe `CollectionPage` \/ `ItemList` pattern remains:\n\n```text\nCollectionPage\n  mainEntity → ItemList\n    itemListElement → ListItem[]\n```\n\nThe Christian Right item on `\/publications\/` points to:\n\n```text\nhttps:\/\/doi.org\/10.1093\/jcs\/csaf039\n```\n\nand the DOI node points to:\n\n```text\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/#review-christian-right-europe-issue\n```\n\nThe Christian Right periodical chain on `\/publications\/` uses page-local node IDs:\n\n```text\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/#review-christian-right-europe-periodical\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/#review-christian-right-europe-volume\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/#review-christian-right-europe-issue\n```\n\nThis is acceptable for Stage 3, even though the dedicated review page uses its\nown local node IDs:\n\n```text\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#periodical\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#volume\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/reviews\/christian-right-europe\/#issue\n```\n\nDecision: canonicalising periodical\/volume\/issue node IDs across pages is not\nnecessary for the current task and can be deferred.\n\n## Cosmic Connections periodical metadata on `\/publications\/`\n\nThe `\/publications\/` page also includes a periodical chain for the Cosmic\nConnections DOI article.\n\nCurrent DOI node:\n\n```text\nhttps:\/\/doi.org\/10.1177\/13684310241249684\n```\n\nCurrent periodical chain on `\/publications\/`:\n\n```text\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/#review-cosmic-connections-periodical\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/#review-cosmic-connections-volume\nhttps:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/#review-cosmic-connections-issue\n```\n\nCurrent metadata:\n\n```text\nPeriodical:\nEuropean Journal of Social Theory\n\nPeriodical URL:\nhttps:\/\/journals.sagepub.com\/home\/EST\n\nISSNs:\n1368-4310\n1461-7137\n\nPublisher:\nSage Publications\n\nVolume:\n28\n\nVolume URL:\nhttps:\/\/journals.sagepub.com\/toc\/esta\/28\n\nIssue:\n2\n\nIssue URL:\nhttps:\/\/journals.sagepub.com\/toc\/esta\/28\/2\n\nIssue datePublished:\n2025-05\n```\n\nThe Cosmic Connections DOI node includes page information:\n\n```json\n\"pagination\": \"339–42\",\n\"pageStart\": \"339\",\n\"pageEnd\": \"342\"\n```\n\nThis is acceptable.\n\nHowever, Cosmic Connections still has this date on `\/publications\/`:\n\n```json\n\"datePublished\": \"2024-05-24T12:00:00+01:00\"\n```\n\nThis should later be reduced to:\n\n```json\n\"datePublished\": \"2024-05-24\"\n```\n\nunless the noon timestamp is verified and meaningful.\n\n## Deferred adjacent cleanup\n\nThe periodical\/volume\/issue task is complete, but the following adjacent issues\nremain for future metadata\/date cleanup:\n\n1. Verify Christian Right issue-level date:\n\n```json\n\"datePublished\": \"2025-07-01\"\n```\n\nIf not exact, reduce to `2025-07` or omit.\n\n2. Clean date precision on `\/publications\/`, especially:\n\n```json\n\"datePublished\": \"2024-05-24T12:00:00+01:00\"\n```\n\nfor Cosmic Connections.\n\n3. Check year-only or month-only publication dates currently represented as\ninvented 1 January dates, e.g.:\n\n```json\n\"datePublished\": \"2025-01-01\"\n\"datePublished\": \"2023-01-01\"\n```\n\nUse exact dates where known; otherwise avoid invented day\/month precision.\n\n4. `\/publications\/` schema still uses old “Dr Stevan Veljkovic” strings:\n\n```json\n\"name\": \"Publications | Dr Stevan Veljkovic\"\n\"description\": \"Publications of Dr Stevan Veljkovic.\"\n\"name\": \"Publications of Dr Stevan Veljkovic\"\n```\n\nThese should eventually be aligned with the adopted title\/name system:\n\n```text\nWebSite.name \/ Person.name \/ og:site_name → Stevan Veljkovic\nordinary page title → Publications | Stevan Veljkovic\nsemantic page\/list name → Publications\n```\n\nPossible future values:\n\n```json\n\"name\": \"Publications\"\n\"description\": \"Publications of Stevan Veljkovic.\"\n```\n\nand:\n\n```json\n\"name\": \"Publications of Stevan Veljkovic\"\n```\n\n5. Publication-list review entries are currently mostly typed as:\n\n```json\n\"@type\": \"ScholarlyArticle\"\n```\n\nFor review items, it may later be more precise to use:\n\n```json\n\"@type\": [\"ScholarlyArticle\", \"Review\"]\n```\n\nThis is optional and not a blocker.\n\n6. For true Version of Record cases, the future model may be simplified so that\nthe `WebPage.mainEntity` points directly to the DOI review node. For now, the\nexisting distinction between DOI node and local `#review` node remains accepted.\n\n## Current decision\n\nThe `add periodical\/volume\/issue nodes` task can be marked complete.\n\nThe next org-mode task, `Add firstPublishedOnline value`, can safely proceed.\n\n```\n","refusal":null,"role":"assistant"},{"content":"26 May 2026 at 15:54:46 BST\n\n# Questions about firstPublishedOnline idea\n\nIn academic publishing a distinction is often made between the date of first \/ online publication and the ‘hard’ date which goes along with a periodical volume and issue. For instance, my cosmic-connections review was first published in May 2024 and didn’t appear in a volume and issue until nearly a year later. It would seem worth capturing such details in metadata because a citation will display a date of publication that might be very different from a real (officially recognised) date of first publication. I understand (from the Chicago Manual of Style 18) that publishers do often regard the true date of publication as the date when an article appeared online.\n\nSo what would be a sensible way for me to proceed on this point in my project? I already adopt the convention in my intro blocks of giving a citation in Chicago format and then below that citation printing a short note that just says ‘first published online [etc],’ which seems similar to how journals operate, as these often display such notes on pages for articles.","role":"user"},{"annotations":[],"content":"A sensible way to proceed is to treat **“first published online” as the article\/review’s real `datePublished`**, and to treat the later volume\/issue appearance as **container metadata on the `PublicationIssue` node**.\n\nIn other words, do **not** try to put two competing `datePublished` values on the same article node. You now have the right graph structure to separate them cleanly:\n\n```text\nPublished DOI article\/review\n  datePublished → first online publication date\n\nPublicationIssue\n  datePublished → issue\/cover\/issue-release date, if known\n```\n\nThat is exactly the kind of distinction your new periodical\/volume\/issue nodes make possible.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Do not invent a `firstPublishedOnline` Schema.org property\n\nSchema.org does not have a standard, widely understood property called:\n\n```json\n\"firstPublishedOnline\"\n```\n\nSo I would **not** emit this directly in JSON-LD under the Schema.org context:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"firstPublishedOnline\": \"2024-05-24\"\n}\n```\n\nIt may not break anything, but it will be non-standard and likely ignored. It may also produce validator warnings depending on the validator.\n\nInstead, use `firstPublishedOnline` as an **internal content\/frontmatter field**, then map it to standard Schema.org properties.\n\nRecommended principle:\n\n```text\nfrontmatter firstPublishedOnline → JSON-LD datePublished on the DOI article node\nfrontmatter issueDatePublished   → JSON-LD datePublished on PublicationIssue\n```\n\n---\n\n## 2. Recommended project convention\n\nAdopt this convention:\n\n### For the DOI\/publisher version of a journal article or review\n\nUse:\n\n```json\n\"datePublished\": \"2024-05-24\"\n```\n\nto mean the official first publication date of the article\/review, normally the first online publication date.\n\n### For the periodical issue\n\nUse:\n\n```json\n\"datePublished\": \"2025-05\"\n```\n\nor:\n\n```json\n\"datePublished\": \"2025-07-01\"\n```\n\non the `PublicationIssue` node only if this describes the issue itself.\n\nSo for Cosmic Connections, conceptually:\n\n```text\nDOI article:\ndatePublished → 2024-05-24\n\nIssue:\nvolumeNumber → 28\nissueNumber → 2\ndatePublished → 2025-05\n```\n\nThis says:\n\n> The article was first published online in May 2024, and later belonged to volume 28, issue 2, May 2025.\n\nThat is exactly the distinction you want.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Recommended frontmatter shape\n\nFor your review\/publication metadata, I would use something like this.\n\n### Cosmic Connections\n\n```yaml\npublishedReview:\n  doi: \"10.1177\/13684310241249684\"\n  url: \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1177\/13684310241249684\"\n\n  firstPublishedOnline: \"2024-05-24\"\n\n  periodical:\n    name: \"European Journal of Social Theory\"\n    url: \"https:\/\/journals.sagepub.com\/home\/EST\"\n    issn:\n      - \"1368-4310\"\n      - \"1461-7137\"\n    publisher: \"Sage Publications\"\n\n  volume: \"28\"\n  issue: \"2\"\n  issueDatePublished: \"2025-05\"\n  issueUrl: \"https:\/\/journals.sagepub.com\/toc\/esta\/28\/2\"\n\n  pagination: \"339–42\"\n  pageStart: \"339\"\n  pageEnd: \"342\"\n```\n\nThen generate the DOI node as:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"@id\": \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1177\/13684310241249684\",\n  \"@type\": [\n    \"ScholarlyArticle\",\n    \"Review\"\n  ],\n  \"datePublished\": \"2024-05-24\",\n  \"isPartOf\": {\n    \"@id\": \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/#review-cosmic-connections-issue\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\nand the issue node as:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"@id\": \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/#review-cosmic-connections-issue\",\n  \"@type\": \"PublicationIssue\",\n  \"issueNumber\": \"2\",\n  \"datePublished\": \"2025-05\",\n  \"isPartOf\": {\n    \"@id\": \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/publications\/#review-cosmic-connections-volume\"\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. What to do with the existing `datePublished` field\n\nYou need to avoid ambiguity in your content model.\n\nI would recommend this rule:\n\n```text\npublishedReview.firstPublishedOnline\n  = the official first online publication date, if known\n\npublishedReview.datePublished\n  = optional fallback only when firstPublishedOnline is not separately supplied\n\npublishedReview.issueDatePublished\n  = date\/month\/year of the periodical issue itself, not the article\n```\n\nThen in the JSON-LD generator:\n\n```ts\nconst articleDatePublished =\n  review.publishedReview?.firstPublishedOnline ??\n  review.publishedReview?.datePublished;\n```\n\nand:\n\n```ts\nif (articleDatePublished) {\n  publishedReviewNode.datePublished = articleDatePublished;\n}\n```\n\nFor the issue node:\n\n```ts\nif (review.publishedReview?.issueDatePublished) {\n  issueNode.datePublished = review.publishedReview.issueDatePublished;\n}\n```\n\nThis lets you keep old metadata working while gradually migrating to the more precise model.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Keep the visible “first published online” note\n\nYour current visible convention sounds good and scholarly:\n\n```text\nFirst published online 24 May 2024.\n```\n\nI would keep it.\n\nBetter still, generate that visible note from the same metadata field used for JSON-LD:\n\n```yaml\nfirstPublishedOnline: \"2024-05-24\"\n```\n\nThen render it as:\n\n```text\nFirst published online 24 May 2024.\n```\n\nThis avoids the risk of the visible text and JSON-LD drifting apart.\n\nIf a review was first published online and assigned to a volume\/issue at the same time, the note is optional. If the dates differ materially, as with Cosmic Connections, the note is useful.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Do not use invented noon timestamps\n\nFor Cosmic Connections, replace:\n\n```json\n\"datePublished\": \"2024-05-24T12:00:00+01:00\"\n```\n\nwith:\n\n```json\n\"datePublished\": \"2024-05-24\"\n```\n\nunless noon is a real publisher-supplied timestamp.\n\nFor scholarly publication metadata, date-only values are preferable unless the exact time is meaningful.\n\n---\n\n## 7. How this affects citations\n\nYou can keep citation formatting separate from the semantic date model.\n\nYou may need three distinct concepts:\n\n```text\nfirstPublishedOnline\n  Real first online publication date.\n\nissueDatePublished\n  Date\/month\/year attached to the issue.\n\ncitationHtml\n  The exact human citation you want to display.\n```\n\nFor example, a citation might say:\n\n```html\nEuropean Journal of Social Theory 28, no. 2 (2025): 339–42.\n```\n\nwhile the note below says:\n\n```text\nFirst published online 24 May 2024.\n```\n\nand JSON-LD says:\n\n```json\n\"datePublished\": \"2024-05-24\"\n```\n\non the article node.\n\nThat is not contradictory. It records two different publication facts:\n\n1. first online publication in 2024;\n2. later volume\/issue assignment in 2025.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Sorting and grouping should remain a separate decision\n\nBe careful not to force the bibliography’s visual ordering to follow `datePublished`.\n\nYou may eventually want separate fields such as:\n\n```yaml\nsortDate: \"2025-05\"\ncitationYear: \"2025\"\nfirstPublishedOnline: \"2024-05-24\"\n```\n\nor:\n\n```yaml\ndisplayYear: \"2025\"\nsortDate: \"2025-05\"\nfirstPublishedOnline: \"2024-05-24\"\n```\n\nWhy? Because a bibliography may reasonably group an article under the year of its volume\/issue or citation, even if the article was first available online earlier.\n\nFor Stage 3, do not overcomplicate this unless the current ordering is wrong. But conceptually, keep these separate:\n\n```text\nJSON-LD publication date ≠ necessarily bibliography grouping year\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. Concrete implementation steps\n\n### Step 1: Add schema fields\n\nIn `src\/content.config.ts`, add optional fields to the relevant review\/publication item schema:\n\n```ts\nfirstPublishedOnline: z.string().optional(),\nissueDatePublished: z.string().optional(),\nissueDateLabel: z.string().optional(),\n```\n\nWhere they belong depends on your current frontmatter shape, but likely under:\n\n```ts\npublishedReview\n```\n\nFor example:\n\n```ts\npublishedReview: z.object({\n  doi: z.string().optional(),\n  url: z.string().url().optional(),\n\n  datePublished: z.string().optional(),\n  firstPublishedOnline: z.string().optional(),\n\n  periodical: z.object({\n    name: z.string(),\n    url: z.string().url().optional(),\n    issn: z.array(z.string()).optional(),\n    publisher: z.string().optional(),\n  }).optional(),\n\n  volume: z.string().optional(),\n  issue: z.string().optional(),\n  issueDatePublished: z.string().optional(),\n  issueDateLabel: z.string().optional(),\n  issueUrl: z.string().url().optional(),\n\n  articleId: z.string().optional(),\n  pagination: z.string().optional(),\n  pageStart: z.string().optional(),\n  pageEnd: z.string().optional(),\n}).optional()\n```\n\n---\n\n### Step 2: Update JSON-LD article date logic\n\nIn the review schema generator and publications schema generator, use:\n\n```ts\nconst datePublished =\n  publishedReview.firstPublishedOnline ??\n  publishedReview.datePublished;\n```\n\nThen set:\n\n```ts\nif (datePublished) {\n  articleNode.datePublished = datePublished;\n}\n```\n\nThis means `firstPublishedOnline` becomes the preferred article-level publication date.\n\n---\n\n### Step 3: Update issue-node date logic\n\nIn your periodical\/container helper, set issue `datePublished` from issue metadata only:\n\n```ts\nif (container.issueDatePublished) {\n  issue.datePublished = container.issueDatePublished;\n}\n```\n\nDo **not** let the article’s `firstPublishedOnline` leak onto the issue node.\n\n---\n\n### Step 4: Update Cosmic Connections metadata\n\nCosmic Connections is the important test case.\n\nSet:\n\n```yaml\npublishedReview:\n  firstPublishedOnline: \"2024-05-24\"\n  issueDatePublished: \"2025-05\"\n```\n\nThen make sure the generated JSON-LD says:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"@id\": \"https:\/\/doi.org\/10.1177\/13684310241249684\",\n  \"datePublished\": \"2024-05-24\"\n}\n```\n\nand:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"@type\": \"PublicationIssue\",\n  \"issueNumber\": \"2\",\n  \"datePublished\": \"2025-05\"\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Step 5: Update Christian Right metadata\n\nFor Christian Right, if first online publication is the same as the DOI publication date, use:\n\n```yaml\npublishedReview:\n  firstPublishedOnline: \"2025-07-25\"\n  issueDatePublished: \"2025-07\"\n```\n\nor, only if verified:\n\n```yaml\n  issueDatePublished: \"2025-07-01\"\n```\n\nThen the DOI node should keep:\n\n```json\n\"datePublished\": \"2025-07-25\"\n```\n\nand the issue node should have the issue date\/month separately.\n\n---\n\n### Step 6: Generate visible notes from the same field\n\nWherever your intro block currently renders the “first published online” note, prefer to generate it from:\n\n```yaml\npublishedReview.firstPublishedOnline\n```\n\nFor example:\n\n```astro\n{review.publishedReview?.firstPublishedOnline && (\n  <p class=\"review_publication_note\">\n    First published online {formatDisplayDate(review.publishedReview.firstPublishedOnline)}.\n  <\/p>\n)}\n```\n\nUse an en-GB display formatter:\n\n```text\n2024-05-24 → 24 May 2024\n2025-05    → May 2025\n2025       → 2025\n```\n\n---\n\n## 10. Optional but not necessary: `PublicationEvent`\n\nIf you later want a more explicit machine-readable representation of “first online publication”, you could investigate Schema.org `PublicationEvent`.\n\nBut for now, I would **not** add this unless you have a clear reason. It is extra complexity and probably less useful than simply using:\n\n```json\n\"datePublished\": \"2024-05-24\"\n```\n\non the article node.\n\nThe clean Stage 3 model should be:\n\n```text\nArticle\/review datePublished = first online publication date\nIssue datePublished = issue date\/month\/year\nVisible note = generated from firstPublishedOnline\nCitation = human citation, may use issue year\n```\n\n---\n\n## Recommended decision\n\nFor this project, adopt the following rule:\n\n```text\nFor DOI-identified journal articles\/reviews, `datePublished` in JSON-LD should\nmean the publisher-recognised first publication date, normally first online\npublication.\n\nThe later volume\/issue date should be modelled on the `PublicationIssue` node,\nnot by overwriting the article’s `datePublished`.\n\nThe internal\/frontmatter field `firstPublishedOnline` may be used to make this\nexplicit and to generate the visible “First published online …” note, but it\nshould map to standard Schema.org `datePublished`, not to a non-standard\n`firstPublishedOnline` JSON-LD property.\n```\n\nThat gives you truthful metadata, matches academic publishing practice, preserves your visible citation-note convention, and fits naturally with the periodical\/volume\/issue nodes you just added.","refusal":null,"role":"assistant"},{"content":"26 May 2026 at 16:38:10 BST\n\n# Cosmic Connections JSON-LD verification\n\nThis is now the JSON-LD from the cosmic-connections review page\n\n```json\n{\n      \"@context\": \"https:\/\/schema.org\",\n      \"@graph\": [\n        {\n          \"@id\": \"https:\/\/orcid.org\/0000-0002-2599-3227\",\n          \"@type\": \"Person\",\n          \"name\": \"Stevan Veljkovic\",\n          \"url\": \"https:\/\/stevanveljkovic.com\/\",\n          \"identifier\": {\n            \"@type\": \"PropertyValue\",\n            \"propertyID\": \"ORCID\",\n            \"value\": \"0000-0002-2599-3227\",\n            \"url\": \"https:\/\/orcid.org\/0000-00